[{"sha":"41ad65049b13213b6119b7d07a264e2b2661c72b","author":{"email":"d2f798c68dab979d539dfeddebc6b96a78f505a8@google.com","name":"Edward Schwartz"},"message":"Add caution to math.unsorted_segment_* documentation about bad segment_ids on GPU

In `tf.math`, `unsorted_segment_max`, `unsorted_segment_mean`, `unsorted_segment_min`, `unsorted_segment_prod`, `unsorted_segment_sqrt_n` and `unsorted_segment_sum` all expect that `segments_ids` are less than `num_segments`. On CPU, these are validated, and an error is thrown for out-of-bounds indices. On Gpu, these are NOT validated, and out-of-bound indices do not throw an error but instead result in safe but unspecified behavior.

[{"sha":"53a37d7a5291d191a4d578e65b1983e304b6f834","author":{"email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com","name":"Smit Hinsu"},"message":"Fix Gather op bounds inference

Gather op should get indices as constant and not as upper/lower bound as the default implementation does. Getting only the upper bound with fetch a particular value from data at the lowest or the highest index which is incorrect.

For example,

data = [3, 2]
indices = sort([0, 1])

Getting the upper bound on indices will return [1, 1], making the gather result bound [2, 2] and not [3, 2].

[{"sha":"54441d239c4103f36c0080d1a6ac83e1e06f942b","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Cache the results of list_children when exporting SavedModel, and trigger function side effects before gathering the children.

As part of the SavedModel layering project, `Trackable` will have a single function that returns all Trackable children -- functions included. That means that the following will be combined into a single function:
- `_checkpoint_dependencies`
- `_list_extra_dependencies_for_serialization`
- `_list_functions_for_serialization`

Currently, SavedModel caches the result to `_list_functions_for_serialization`, but not for the other methods. Why? Because the functions returned from `_list_functions_for_serialization` can trigger side effects when tracing (such as adding a variable to the `Trackable`).

We need to keep the guarantee that children are only gathered a single time, because in many cases (such as the `Resource` class), new tf.functions are generated each time. In `Resource`, a new init/create/destroy function is generated inside `_list_functions_for_serialization`.

Therefore, SavedModel saving must cache the results to `list_children`, while at the same time triggering the function tracing and side effects in the appropriate manner.
